# Macrotide — operator config. Copy to `.env.local` and fill what you need.
# `.env.local` is gitignored; commit only this template.
#
# Canonical reference for every env var the app reads (defaults, code
# locations, behavior contracts) lives in AGENTS.md § Environment variables.
# This file is the operator setup template — kept self-contained on purpose
# so a fresh clone can boot without flipping between docs.

# ─── App URL ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Used for OpenRouter referer + WebAuthn passkey origin in production.
# In dev, http://localhost:3000 is always trusted.
PUBLIC_APP_URL=http://localhost:3000

# Dev-only: one extra origin to trust for the dev server when you reach it
# through a reverse proxy or remote host instead of localhost (Codespaces, a
# LAN IP, an SSH/tunnel hostname). Wired to Next's `allowedDevOrigins` in
# next.config.ts. Hostname only, no scheme. Leave unset for plain localhost dev.
# DEV_ALLOWED_ORIGIN=my-host.example.ts.net

# ─── Auth (better-auth + passkey) ──────────────────────────────────────────
# Auth is REQUIRED by default — the dashboard bounces to /login until
# a passkey is registered. Secure-by-default: misconfiguring (e.g. exposing
# the port) fails closed, not open. See SECURITY.md for the threat model.
#
# Opt out ONLY for local dev when you're the sole user on loopback:
# AUTH_DISABLED=1

# Generate with `openssl rand -base64 32`. Required when auth is enabled.
# The code has a "macrotide-dev-secret-change-me" fallback so `npm run dev`
# works without setup, but you MUST set this in any real deployment.
# AUTH_SECRET=

# Optional — Relying Party config. Defaults: rpName="Macrotide", rpID inferred
# from PUBLIC_APP_URL host. Override only if you understand WebAuthn rpID rules.
# AUTH_RP_NAME=Macrotide
# AUTH_RP_ID=macrotide.example.com

# ─── Owner account (multi-user) ────────────────────────────────────────────
# Names the owner account. Two uses, so keep it in the RUNNING app's env (not
# just for the one-off script):
#   1. Backfill script — `npx tsx --env-file=.env.local scripts/backfill-owner.ts`
#      finds (or creates) this user, attaches every NULL-owned app row to it,
#      and grants the `trusted` tier. Idempotent; a no-op when unset.
#   2. Runtime — the owner-only admin UI (list users, flip free↔trusted) gates
#      on session email == OWNER_EMAIL. FAIL-CLOSED: unset → nobody is owner,
#      the admin API 403s, and the menu entry is hidden.
# Safe to leave blank on fresh single-user installs.
# OWNER_EMAIL=you@example.com

# ─── Google OAuth (optional, env-gated) ────────────────────────────────────
# The "Continue with Google" button appears on /login ONLY when both the id
# and secret are set. Unset → the app stays passkey-only, no config needed.
# OAuth callback URI to register with Google:
#   <PUBLIC_APP_URL>/api/auth/callback/google
# GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=
# GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET=

# ─── Signup bot protection — Cloudflare Turnstile (optional) ───────────────
# When TURNSTILE_SECRET_KEY is UNSET, signup/OAuth token verification is
# BYPASSED (treated as a pass) so local dev works with no setup. Set both in
# production. TURNSTILE_SITE_KEY is public and shipped to the browser.
# TURNSTILE_SITE_KEY=
# TURNSTILE_SECRET_KEY=

# ─── Legal pages (operator-configurable) ──────────────────────────────────
# The /legal/terms + /legal/privacy pages read these so the repo ships nothing
# operator-specific. All optional — unset values fall back to neutral wording.
#   OPERATOR_NAME      — shown as who runs this instance. Unset → "a single
#                        individual" / "the operator".
#   CONTACT_EMAIL      — contact shown on both pages (rendered as a mailto).
#                        Unset → no email, just "contact the operator". NOTE:
#                        no fallback to OWNER_EMAIL — set this only if you want
#                        a real address published publicly.
#   LEGAL_JURISDICTION — governing-law jurisdiction (e.g. "Thailand"). Unset →
#                        the governing-law clause is omitted entirely.
# The "Last updated" date is a constant (LEGAL_LAST_UPDATED) in
# lib/legal/config.ts — bump it when you edit the legal copy.
# OPERATOR_NAME=
# CONTACT_EMAIL=
# LEGAL_JURISDICTION=

# ─── AI provider (OpenRouter) ──────────────────────────────────────────────
# Macrotide routes all chat through OpenRouter (one key, every major model).
# Sign up at https://openrouter.ai to get a key; pricing is per-token credit.
#
# OPENROUTER_API_KEY=sk-or-...
#
# Model chain (comma-separated, first is primary, rest are fallbacks).
# Default: `openrouter/free,openrouter/auto` — try free models first, fall
# back to paid `auto` only if every free model is unavailable. Override with
# any model id from openrouter.ai/models (e.g. `anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.5`).
# Also used by `tier='trusted'` users.
# TRUSTED_TIER_MODELS=openrouter/free,openrouter/auto
#
# RECOMMENDED for a real "smart advisor" (owner + trusted). The reasoning-intent
# gate means a thinking model only burns reasoning on review/plan turns, so a
# capable model stays token-efficient on the common lookup turn. Picks below come
# from the calibrated, Opus-judged model sweep on the complex-tier advisor task
# (2026-06-11; full results + method in docs/explanation/research/agent-evals.md):
#
#   TRUSTED_TIER_MODELS=x-ai/grok-4.3,z-ai/glm-5.1
#
#   - x-ai/grok-4.3 (primary) — best BALANCE: quality 4.43/5, just 3% dead-ends,
#     and ~9s/turn (4-8x faster than the rest), concise. Fast + reliable is what
#     makes an advisor *feel* good in a live chat.
#   - z-ai/glm-5.1 (fallback) — highest quality in the sweep (4.55/5); a DIFFERENT
#     provider than grok, so a single-provider outage can't take out both. Only
#     runs when grok is unavailable, so its slower/pricier profile doesn't matter.
#   - Cost: input tokens dominate, and grok supports prompt caching (cached read
#     ~16% of input). The system prompt + tools + frozen memory are a cache-stable
#     prefix, so real cost runs ~$11-13 per 1k complex turns — below the list rate.
#
# Other sweep candidates: minimax/minimax-m3 is cheapest but ~78s/turn + verbose;
# moonshotai/kimi-k2.6 is slow + dead-ends. z-ai/glm-4.6 (the brief interim pick
# this replaces) dead-ended ~28% of complex turns (the "feels broken" failure) —
# that reliability gap, not raw smarts, is why grok wins it. Frontier ceiling (pricey):
# openai/gpt-5.5 / anthropic/claude-opus-4.8. Pick the primary for what you want
# MOST (the chain falls back only on failure); keep a different-provider fallback.
#
# Public-tier (tier='public') chat model. Read from this OWN var, NEVER from
# TRUSTED_TIER_MODELS — a slip in the trusted chain can't widen public access.
# Defaults to the zero-cost router (openrouter/free). Point it at a cheap PAID
# model to lift public-tier quality (bounded by the daily token cap + the
# optional cents cost cap below).
# PUBLIC_TIER_MODELS=openrouter/free
# PUBLIC_TIER_MODELS=google/gemini-2.5-flash    # recommended: cheap, reliable, fast

# Reasoning-intent gate (#58). On the owner/trusted paths, a cheap deterministic
# classifier raises reasoning effort to "medium" only on genuine multi-step turns
# (rebalance, SSF-vs-RMF, a plan-anchored tilt) and "none" otherwise — so
# reasoning rates are paid only where they help. Public/demo always stay "none".
# Set to "off" to restore each model's default reasoning on owner/trusted.
# REASONING_GATE=on

# Advisor turn diagnostics. Set to "1" to log one line per chat turn to the
# server console — served model, the step/finish-reason chain, and each tool
# call's full input (the extracted rows). Local-dev debugging aid; leave unset
# in production. The durable per-turn record is the chat_messages.cards column.
# DEBUG_ADVISOR=1

# ─── AI tier quotas (authenticated users only) ─────────────────────────────
# Per-user daily caps, checked BEFORE forwarding to OpenRouter; reset at UTC
# midnight. Owner / AUTH_DISABLED mode is never metered; demo is bounded by its
# turn cap. Either cap tripping blocks the turn.
#
# Token cap — always on (the floor). Malformed/≤0 → the default.
# DAILY_TOKEN_BUDGET_PUBLIC=20000
# DAILY_TOKEN_BUDGET_TRUSTED=200000
#
# Cost cap (US cents/day) — OPTIONAL, OFF unless set. The right bound when
# PUBLIC_TIER_MODELS is a paid model with asymmetric in/out pricing. Unset or
# malformed → disabled (no invented money cap; the token cap still applies).
# DAILY_CENTS_BUDGET_PUBLIC=50
# DAILY_CENTS_BUDGET_TRUSTED=500
#
# Price table feeding the cost estimate — JSON keyed by the model id OpenRouter
# reports back, values in USD per 1M tokens, merged over the built-in defaults.
# Set it to match PUBLIC_TIER_MODELS. Unpriced (free) models contribute 0 cost.
# MODEL_PRICES={"google/gemini-2.5-flash":{"in":0.3,"out":2.5}}

# ─── AI provider (demo-side) ───────────────────────────────────────────────
# Demo chat is routed through a separate key so demo usage can never burn
# your owner key's quota. Capped at 10 turns per demo session.
#
# Easiest setup: leave DEMO_OPENROUTER_API_KEY unset — demo falls back to
# OPENROUTER_API_KEY, and the default `openrouter/free` (no paid fallback)
# picks zero-cost models per request. Demo errors cleanly if free is
# unavailable rather than silently billing.
#
# For stricter isolation, create a second OpenRouter key and set:
# DEMO_OPENROUTER_API_KEY=sk-or-...
# DEMO_TIER_MODELS=openrouter/free                          # default; no fallback
# DEMO_TIER_MODELS=meta-llama/llama-3.3-70b-instruct:free   # pin a specific one

# ─── AI provider (ancillary cheap models) ─────────────────────────────────
# Small background tasks that don't justify Claude/GPT spend. Both reuse
# OPENROUTER_API_KEY and default to `openrouter/free` (cheap free-model
# router). Leave unset unless you want to pin a specific small model.
#
# TITLE_MODELS  — auto-titling a chat after its first turn pair (3–5 words).
# EXTRACT_MODELS — archive-time durable-fact extraction. Falls back
#                 to TITLE_MODELS, then `openrouter/free`. Decoupled from
#                 TITLE_MODELS so you can pin a slightly better model for
#                 extraction (it writes durable memory) without affecting titles.
# TITLE_MODELS=openrouter/free
# EXTRACT_MODELS=openrouter/free

# ─── AI provider (Image OCR for Add holdings) ──────────────────────────────
# Powers the "Image" tab of the Add holdings sheet — user uploads a broker
# screenshot, we ask a vision model to extract proposed rows for review.
#
# Default model chain:
#   primary  = baidu/qianfan-ocr-fast:free   (zero cost, 27.2M tokens/week)
#   fallback = baidu/qianfan-ocr-fast        (paid, ~$0.004/call, no-train)
# Both are the same Baidu OCR model with the same transcription quality.
# The route catches provider-unavailable errors (rate limit, quota) on the
# primary and retries automatically against the fallback before returning a
# 502 to the UI. When you pin OCR_MODEL, the default fallback is disabled —
# set OCR_FALLBACK_MODEL explicitly if you want a safety net.
#
# Operator-verified (2026-05-23): qianfan-ocr-fast:free is no-train despite
# being a :free variant. Re-verify before any public deploy.
#
# Alternatives:
# - `qwen/qwen3-vl-32b-instruct` — $0.00094/call, large general-purpose vision,
#   no-train. Good fallback candidate.
# - `openrouter/free` (free-models router) — requires "Free endpoints that
#   may train on request data" enabled at
#   https://openrouter.ai/settings/privacy. Often fast-fails for vision input.
# - `anthropic/claude-haiku-4.5` — paid, no-train, highest quality + reasoning.
#
# OCR_MODEL=baidu/qianfan-ocr-fast:free
# OCR_FALLBACK_MODEL=baidu/qianfan-ocr-fast

# ─── AI provider (in-chat vision) ──────────────────────────────────────────
# Vision model for an image-bearing CHAT turn (the Advisor "sees" images you
# attach in chat, reconciles multiple screenshots into holdings, answers chart
# questions). Separate from OCR_MODEL (the Add-holdings importer) and read from
# its OWN var — never TRUSTED_TIER_MODELS/PUBLIC_TIER_MODELS — so public-tier vision can't
# widen the text model chains. Must be vision-capable; comma-separated fallback
# chain accepted. Owner/trusted/public all use it; public-tier image turns are bounded by
# the daily token + optional cents caps. Attached images are sent to this
# provider to answer the turn and cached only in the user's browser — never
# stored on the server. Set to `off` to disable inline chat vision entirely
# (image turns then get a stub pointing at the Add-holdings importer).
# VISION_CHAT_MODEL=google/gemini-2.5-flash
# VISION_CHAT_MODEL=off                        # disable inline chat vision
#
# DEMO_VISION — allow demo (anonymous "Try the demo") sessions to upload images
# in chat. Off by default: demo hides the attach button and stubs image turns.
# When on, demo image turns use VISION_CHAT_MODEL with DEMO_OPENROUTER_API_KEY,
# bounded by the 10-turn demo cap.
# DEMO_VISION=off

# ─── Database ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# The database is split along a lifecycle boundary into two SQLite files
# (both auto-created, both under data/):
#   - app.db    — system of record: accounts, buckets, holdings, plans, chat,
#                 preferences. Precious; backed up nightly.
#   - market.db — regenerable market data: fund catalog/fees, the NAV/quote
#                 cache, feeder look-through. Rebuilt from upstream; NOT backed up.
# DB_PATH=data/app.db
# MARKET_DB_PATH=data/market.db

# ─── Market data — indices / FX / stocks (Twelve Data, keyed) ──────────────
# Primary source for the Markets-screen indicators (default set: S&P 500,
# Nasdaq-100, MSCI ACWI, gold, USD/THB, Thailand — via free-tier ETF proxies;
# users can add more from the catalog) and any market-sourced holding. Yahoo
# Finance (the keyless fallback)
# now hard-blocks datacenter IPs with HTTP 429, so a keyed source is needed for
# reliable data in production.
#
# How it works (provider chain), preferred → fallback for a `market`-sourced
# symbol:
#   FMP (keyed, REAL US indices)
#     → EODHD (keyed, REAL global indices + the Thai SET index)
#       → Twelve Data (keyed, ETF proxies)
#         → Frankfurter (keyless, FX only)
#           → Yahoo (keyless)
# Each provider only matches the symbols it actually serves, and the keyed ones
# drop out of the chain entirely when their env var is unset. So with NO keys at
# all the chain is exactly Frankfurter (FX) → Yahoo, and with only this Twelve
# Data key set you get the prior ETF-proxy behaviour — nothing breaks before the
# FMP/EODHD keys exist.
#
# FX pairs (USD/THB) fall back to ECB-backed Frankfurter, which — unlike Yahoo —
# needs no key and doesn't block datacenter IPs, so USD/THB works with NO key.
#
# Get a free key: sign up at https://twelvedata.com (free tier ≈ 800 req/day,
# 8 req/min). NOTE: raw index symbols (S&P 500, Nasdaq-100, SET, …) are NOT on
# the free plan — but their US-listed tracking ETFs are, so Twelve Data serves
# the ETF proxy (SPY, QQQ, DIA, THD, …) for an index symbol. Daily % moves match
# the index; the absolute value shown is the ETF's. Use FMP/EODHD below for the
# REAL index level. Keep the key in .env.local only — never commit it.
# TWELVE_DATA_API_KEY=

# ─── FMP — REAL US index levels (optional) ─────────────────────────────────
# Financial Modeling Prep (https://financialmodelingprep.com). Free tier serves
# the actual index level (not an ETF proxy) for the US indices ^GSPC (S&P 500),
# ^NDX (Nasdaq-100) and ^DJI (Dow) via /api/v3/historical-price-full/{symbol}.
# Free tier ≈ 250 calls/day — the most generous quota in the chain — so FMP sits
# FIRST for the US indices it covers. UNSET ⇒ the provider's matches() returns
# false and the chain falls through to EODHD → Twelve Data ETF proxy → Yahoo.
# Key in .env.local only; never logged. Get a key at the URL above.
# FMP_API_KEY=

# ─── EODHD — REAL global index levels + SET (optional) ─────────────────────
# EOD Historical Data (https://eodhd.com). Free tier (≈ 20 calls/day) serves the
# actual index level via the {CODE}.INDX virtual-exchange notation. We map the
# canonical Yahoo-style symbols → EODHD codes: ^GSPC→GSPC.INDX, ^NDX→NDX.INDX,
# ^IXIC→IXIC.INDX, ^DJI→DJI.INDX, ^N225→N225.INDX, and the Thai SET index
# ^SET.BK→SET.INDX. EODHD covers markets FMP's free tier doesn't (Nikkei, SET),
# so it sits SECOND — after FMP, before the Twelve Data ETF proxy. UNSET ⇒
# matches() returns false and the chain falls back to the ETF proxy → Yahoo.
# Key in .env.local only; never logged. Get a key at the URL above.
#
# Note: MSCI ACWI has no free real-index source anywhere and intentionally stays
# an ETF proxy (ACWI); Gold stays the XAU/USD spot commodity (GC=F), not an index.
# EODHD_API_KEY=

# ─── Thai SEC Open API (Thai mutual fund NAVs) ─────────────────────────────
# Powers the `thfund:` provider. Without a key, holdings tagged
# `thfund:...` render as "—".
#
# Portal: https://secopendata.sec.or.th/sec-open-apis
# Sign in → Profile → Subscriptions → Subscribe. The portal generates one
# subscription with TWO keys (Primary + Secondary) shown together — both
# work identically; the Secondary exists for zero-downtime key rotation.
# Paste either one below. One subscription covers all 6 product groups
# (bond, fund, digital-asset, LicenseCheck, onereport, pvd).
#
# Header: Ocp-Apim-Subscription-Key (Azure APIM).
# Rate limit: 5,000 calls / 300 s (HTTP 421 = quota). The gateway ALSO enforces
# a tighter per-second burst cap (HTTP 429). The provider self-throttles to
# ~14 calls/s by default; if a bulk catalog crawl sees sustained 429s (e.g. on a
# key shared with other consumers), raise the spacing below and restart:
#   SEC_MIN_INTERVAL_MS=150   # ≈ 6.7 calls/s — back off under the burst cap
# Also tunable: SEC_MAX_RETRIES, SEC_BASE_DELAY_MS, SEC_MAX_BACKOFF_MS.
# Refresh windows: 09:30 + 17:30 Bangkok time.
#
# The portal warns explicitly: NEVER publish your Subscription Key on
# GitHub, websites, or any public file. .env.local is gitignored — keep
# the key there, never in the committed .env.example.
# SEC_API_KEY=

# ─── SEC fund enrichment (optional, default OFF) ───────────────────────────
# Additional per-fund data fetched during the catalog refresh job.
# Each flag is independent; set to "1" to enable.
# None of these are enabled by default — merging this branch does NOT change
# prod crawl behavior until at least one flag is explicitly set.
#
# SEC_INGEST_PERFORMANCE=1    — fetch all performance types per fund class
#                               (fund/benchmark volatility + return, peer avg).
#                               ~1 extra API call per active fund.
# SEC_INGEST_ALLOCATION=1     — fetch asset allocation by type (%NAV breakdown).
#                               ~1 extra API call per active fund.
# SEC_INGEST_HOLDINGS=1       — fetch top-5 holdings per fund.
#                               ~1 extra API call per active fund.
# SEC_INGEST_PORTFOLIO=1      — fetch full quarterly portfolio + monthly
#                               asset-type summary. WARNING: large funds have
#                               100+ holdings (paginated). This roughly doubles
#                               total crawl API calls. Recommend a weekly
#                               cadence rather than nightly.
#                               ~2–10+ extra API calls per active fund.
# SEC_INGEST_DIVIDENDS=1      — bulk-sweep the FULL dividend payment history
#                               (the endpoint has no date filter, so each pass
#                               re-reads everything — roughly 1k paginated
#                               calls per run). Recommend a weekly cadence.
# SEC_INGEST_PERFORMANCE=
# SEC_INGEST_ALLOCATION=
# SEC_INGEST_HOLDINGS=
# SEC_INGEST_PORTFOLIO=
# SEC_INGEST_DIVIDENDS=

# Legacy v1 FundFactsheet subscription key (SEPARATE product from the v2 key)
# — only used by the one-shot scripts/backfill-aimc-v1.ts AIMC-category
# snapshot. The v1 portal retires 2026-06-30; not part of the nightly crawl.
# SEC_V1_API_KEY=

# ─── External enrichment — feeder fund look-through (free, no auth) ────────
# Fetches a feeder fund's underlying holdings from the master fund's latest SEC
# EDGAR Form NPORT-P filing (official, free, no API key). Only applies to feeder
# funds whose master is a US-registered fund in the built-in registry (see
# lib/market/providers/edgar-nport.ts, EDGAR_FUNDS). Holdings are "as of" the
# last fiscal quarter (NPORT-P is filed within ~60 days of quarter end).
# Adds a couple of HTTP requests per matched feeder fund per crawl run.
# Default OFF; set to "1" to enable.
# EXTERNAL_INGEST_FEEDER_HOLDINGS=
#
# SEC EDGAR requires a User-Agent that declares a contact (else HTTP 403).
# Optional override of the default; format "App/version contact-email".
# SEC_EDGAR_USER_AGENT=

# ─── One-click broker import (optional) ───────────────────────────────────────
# Powers "Connect your broker" (the install wizard + auto-sync). A userscript
# runs on your broker's logged-in orders page, collects every portfolio's order
# history via the broker's own API, and posts it to Macrotide. Broker identity is
# NOT committed to this repo — it comes from a "connector manifest" (DATA only;
# the collector logic stays in-repo and broker-agnostic). Leave unset to hide the
# feature (paste / screenshot import still work).
#
# Provide the manifest ONE of three ways (checked in this order):
#
# 1. A local JSON file (recommended for self-host). See .connectors/example.json
#    for the shape. Real manifests live under .connectors/ and are gitignored.
#    Comma-separate several to run multiple brokers side by side (the Connect
#    wizard then shows a broker picker).
# BROKER_CONNECTOR_PATH=.connectors/your-broker.json
# BROKER_CONNECTOR_PATH=.connectors/broker-a.json,.connectors/broker-b.json
#
# 2. A URL the app fetches the manifest JSON from (for shared/published
#    connectors). Cached briefly; data-only, so low-risk. Also comma-separable.
# BROKER_CONNECTOR_URL=https://example.com/connectors/your-broker.json
#
# Manifest fields: id, displayName, host, planPath, historyPath, pendingPath
# (optional), sourceTag, openUrl (order-history page), loginUrl (first-time login
# start), and an optional `shape` mapping the broker's response field paths
# (including `transport` for cross-origin / header-auth APIs and a date-range
# history mode; omit → built-in defaults). Authoring guide:
# docs/how-to/add-a-broker-connector.md.
#
# 3. Legacy individual env vars (back-compat; superseded by the manifest above):
# BROKER_IMPORT_HOST=orders.example-broker.com
# BROKER_IMPORT_PLAN_PATH=/api/v1/portfolios
# BROKER_IMPORT_HISTORY_PATH=/api/v1/orders/history
# BROKER_IMPORT_PENDING_PATH=/api/v1/orders/pending
# BROKER_IMPORT_SOURCE_TAG=broker
# BROKER_IMPORT_DISPLAY_NAME=Example Broker
# BROKER_IMPORT_OPEN_URL=https://orders.example-broker.com/orders/history
# BROKER_IMPORT_LOGIN_URL=https://www.example-broker.com/dashboard
